07114nam a22012375i 9780691208671DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912086717 a10.1515/97806912086712doi  a(DE-B1597)566893  a(OCoLC)1197835768  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPOL0510002bisacsh04a9012231 aBell, Duncan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDreamworlds of Race :bEmpire and the Utopian Destiny of Anglo-America /cDuncan Bell. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (488 p.) :bNo illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Dreamworlds of Race -- t2. The Dreamer of Dreams: Andrew Carnegie and the Reunion of the Race -- t3. Americanizing the World: W. T. Stead and Cecil J. Rhodes -- t4. Artists in Reality: H. G. Wells and the New Republic -- t5. Machine Dreams: The Angloworld as Science Fiction -- t6. Beyond the Sovereign State: Isopolitan Citizenship and Race Patriotism -- t7. A Messenger of Peace to the World: Racial Utopianism and the Abolition of War -- t8. Conclusion: Unveiling the Sphinx -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow transatlantic thinkers in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries promoted the unification of Britain and the United StatesBetween the late nineteenth century and the First World War an ocean-spanning network of prominent individuals advocated the unification of Britain and the United States. They dreamt of the final consolidation of the Angloworld. Scholars, journalists, politicians, businessmen, and science fiction writers invested the “Anglo-Saxons” with extraordinary power. The most ambitious hailed them as a people destined to bring peace and justice to the earth. More modest visions still imagined them as likely to shape the twentieth century. Dreamworlds of Race explores this remarkable moment in the intellectual history of racial domination, political utopianism, and world order.Focusing on a quartet of extraordinary figures—Andrew Carnegie, W. T. Stead, Cecil J. Rhodes, and H. G. Wells—Duncan Bell shows how unionists on both sides of the Atlantic reimagined citizenship, empire, patriotism, race, war, and peace in their quest to secure global supremacy. Yet even as they dreamt of an Anglo-dominated world, the unionists disagreed over the meaning of race, the legitimacy of imperialism, the nature of political belonging, and the ultimate form and purpose of unification. The racial dreamworld was an object of competing claims and fantasies. Exploring speculative fiction as well as more conventional forms of political writing, Bell reads unionist arguments as expressions of the utopianism circulating through fin-de-siècle Anglo-American culture, and juxtaposes them with pan-Africanist critiques of racial domination and late twentieth-century fictional narratives of Anglo-American empire.Tracing how intellectual elites promoted an ambitious project of political and racial unification between Britain and the United States, Dreamworlds of Race analyzes ideas of empire and world order that reverberate to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAnglo-Saxon race. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Utopias.2bisacsh  aAfro-modern writing.  aAmerican imperialism.  aAmericanization of the world.  aAndrew Carnegie.  aAnglo-American union.  aAnglotopian.  aBrexit.  aBritain.  aCecil Rhodes.  aDrawing the Global Colour Line: White Men's Countries and the International Challenge of Racial Equality.  aH. G. Wells.  aHenry Reynolds.  aMarilyn Lake.  aMichael Kenny.  aNick Pearce.  aShadows of Empire: The Anglosphere in British Politics.  aSrdjan Vucetic.  aT. E. S. Scholes.  aThe Anglosphere: A Genealogy of a Racialized Identity in International Relations.  aUnited States.  aW. E. B. Du Bois.  aW. T. Stead.  abiocultural assemblage.  acitizenship.  acyborg imperium.  aempire.  aevolutionary theory.  afuture racial destiny.  aglobe-spanning cyborg.  apan-African.  apatriotism.  aphilosophical pragmatism.  arace.  aracial peace thesis.  aracial utopianism.  ascience fiction.  asteampunk.  atechnology.  atheological justifications of empire.  autopia.  awar.  awhite racial destiny.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069008840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691208671?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691208671423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691208671/original  a978-3-11-069008-8  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-PLWb2020